Here's the refactored test using TUnit's native `Assert.That(...).ThrowsException()` pattern:

```csharp
using TUnit.Core;

public class OrderProcessorTests
{
    [Test]
    public async Task ProcessOrder_EmptyOrder_ThrowsInvalidOperation()
    {
        var processor = new OrderProcessor();

        var exception = await Assert.That(() => processor.ProcessOrder(new Order()))
            .ThrowsException()
            .OfType<InvalidOperationException>()
            .WithMessage("Order must contain at least one item");
    }
}
```

This uses TUnit's fluent assertion chain to verify the exception type and message in one idiomatic expression — no try/catch needed. `ThrowsException().OfType<T>().WithMessage(...)` handles both the type check and message assertion.
